    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A regular Power of Attorney is like a **goblin's temporary hug**. It's nice, but if the hug breaks, the hug ends. A Durable Power of Attorney is like a **goblin's eternal, unbreakable, slightly radioactive hug**. It's permanent, it doesn't expire, and it doesn't matter if the goblin inside me decides to take over my body, or if my brain decides to go rogue and let the goblin in, this goblin statue will still work exactly as it did before I died.\n\nHere is the legal difference clearly:\n\nA **Regular POA** is valid only while the person signing it is **competent**. If the person loses their mind, gets dementia, or becomes incapacitated, the regular POA **automatically ends**. The person's family or a court would have to step in and appoint a new agent, which is a hassle.\n\nA **Durable POA** is valid **even if the person loses their mind**. The word \"durable\" means it survives the loss of capacity. It stays in effect exactly as it did before the person got sick, even if they can't sign it anymore. The person's family or a court would have to",
