      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is the most critical part of the goblin's contract, and you are absolutely right to ask about the specificity.\n\nIf you want the goblin to manage **only** your bank accounts and house, you absolutely **must** write that specific detail into the Durable Power of Attorney. You cannot leave it vague like a goblin who is too busy eating to remember which specific house you are talking about.\n\nHere is the breakdown:\n\n1.  **The General Clause:** The Durable POA will almost certainly include a general clause stating that the goblin can manage \"all of my financial affairs\" or \"my real estate.\" This is the safety net. It ensures that if the goblin gets a little too greedy and decides to take over your car, the goblin still has the authority to do so.\n2.  **The Specific Clause:** You must add a separate, specific section (or a very detailed paragraph) that says: *\"The goblin may manage my checking accounts, savings, and real estate located at 123 Maple Street, but the goblin shall not manage my car, my dog's food, or my personal bank account at the local grocery store.\"*\n\n**Why this matters",
